00:48:05.120 --> 00:48:11.530
One is that it is my stress, my
problems, my anxiety, my life,

00:48:11.530 --> 00:48:13.750
and I need to get
rid of all this

00:48:13.750 --> 00:48:17.090
so that I can live
a better life.

00:48:17.090 --> 00:48:20.200
Maybe there's subconsciously
their ideas of I

00:48:20.200 --> 00:48:23.440
could be higher or
superior or better

00:48:23.440 --> 00:48:25.420
than others in the world.

00:48:25.420 --> 00:48:28.750
And that could be one
frame of how people

00:48:28.750 --> 00:48:30.760
are approaching meditation.

00:48:30.760 --> 00:48:36.940
And I think for me as a
teacher, it's important to offer

00:48:36.940 --> 00:48:41.680
the second frame of how this
practice works because I

00:48:41.680 --> 00:48:45.920
genuinely feel that this
practice cannot go too far

00:48:45.920 --> 00:48:52.600
if it's just about "my," if
it's consumptive in nature.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:59.740
Because I feel that as we
practice more, these layers

00:48:59.740 --> 00:49:05.260
or membranes of separation,
they start thinning out,

00:49:05.260 --> 00:49:09.070
and we start experiencing
this powerful shared

00:49:09.070 --> 00:49:12.250
humanity with each other.

00:49:12.250 --> 00:49:15.820
And for me, in that sense, this
practice is deeply relational.

00:49:15.820 --> 00:49:20.140
I offer retreats which are all
about relational mindfulness.

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:25.030
And those are ways in which
we start becoming very, very

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:26.530
supportive to each other.

00:49:29.110 --> 00:49:32.830
So I think yeah, to
offer this other frame is

00:49:32.830 --> 00:49:35.800
very important and meaningful.

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:39.015
And then, of course,
it's their choice.

00:49:39.015 --> 00:49:40.380
Yeah.

00:49:40.380 --> 00:49:42.790
AUDIENCE: So most of the
tech world in Silicon Valley

00:49:42.790 --> 00:49:45.720
is going like AI.

00:49:45.720 --> 00:49:48.250
And what you're talking
about is going--

00:49:48.250 --> 00:49:49.000
more machine-like.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:52.810
And there'll be machine
inside of me, outside of me.

00:49:52.810 --> 00:49:54.070
And maybe I'll be a machine.

00:49:54.070 --> 00:49:54.611
I don't know.

00:49:54.611 --> 00:49:56.290
A lot of stuff
going on like that,

00:49:56.290 --> 00:49:59.320
and that's the quote-unquote
"future" that people

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:00.430
are really proud of.

00:50:03.310 --> 00:50:06.550
And you talked about going back
to the wild and nature and back

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:08.800
to the Earth.

00:50:08.800 --> 00:50:10.720
How do you reconcile
those two things?

00:50:10.720 --> 00:50:13.590
Because most of our society
is getting more and more

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:16.470
techno-enabled.

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:19.420
NIRALI SHAH: I cannot
reconcile the two personally.

00:50:19.420 --> 00:50:22.397
And I say that standing
here at Google.

00:50:22.397 --> 00:50:23.680
[LAUGHS]

00:50:23.680 --> 00:50:28.750
I personally feel-- at
least that's my sense--

00:50:28.750 --> 00:50:31.570
is that over time,
as we are becoming

00:50:31.570 --> 00:50:38.320
more AI and more
machine oriented,

00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:42.590
I feel that there will be
communities and people who

00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:44.570
will make a choice.

00:50:44.570 --> 00:50:47.590
And there would be some
who would move more

00:50:47.590 --> 00:50:50.920
towards the Earth and
some who would move more

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:52.870
towards machines.

00:50:52.870 --> 00:50:54.460
I don't think machines are bad.

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:56.080
I don't think technology is bad.

00:50:56.080 --> 00:50:57.460
It can be very helpful.

00:50:57.460 --> 00:50:59.230
I use a lot of technology.

00:50:59.230 --> 00:51:04.120
And there is a lot to be said
around appropriate technology.

00:51:04.120 --> 00:51:11.170
But I feel that technology
which can bring a lot of feeling

00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:15.210
and emotion is very important.

00:51:15.210 --> 00:51:20.110
So to answer your question, I
cannot fully reconcile the two

00:51:20.110 --> 00:51:23.640
because I think the aspect
around feeling, energy,

00:51:23.640 --> 00:51:29.450
emotion is very
real to my practice.

00:51:29.450 --> 00:51:31.860
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
for someone starting out

00:51:31.860 --> 00:51:35.670
in meditation practice
how you would recommend

00:51:35.670 --> 00:51:39.180
starting, if you weren't to
just drop your career and life

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:40.945
and move off to an ashram.

00:51:40.945 --> 00:51:42.210
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:42.210 --> 00:51:46.710
NIRALI SHAH: Yeah, I don't think
it's important to drop your--

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:49.710
I think it's completely,
perfectly possible

00:51:49.710 --> 00:51:52.060
and great to--

00:51:52.060 --> 00:51:55.680
maybe that's authentic
to your experience

00:51:55.680 --> 00:52:00.390
right now is to have a stable
job, have a stable family.

00:52:00.390 --> 00:52:03.660
And that stability can be very
helpful to the practice too.

00:52:03.660 --> 00:52:06.270
So it's very personal.

00:52:06.270 --> 00:52:07.920
How to start?

00:52:07.920 --> 00:52:11.010
There are a few ways.

00:52:11.010 --> 00:52:13.890
There's Insight Meditation
Center in Redwood City.

00:52:13.890 --> 00:52:18.000
Gil Fronsdal is a
wonderful teacher.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:20.280
